    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3105348130" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3105348130" />
    <a title="Selena Reiss" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83837614-selena-reiss"><img alt="Selena Reiss" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609720064p2/83837614.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3105348130?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Selena Reiss" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Selena Reiss" href="/user/show/83837614-selena-reiss">Selena Reiss</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385735087" href="/book/show/7756918-what-they-always-tell-us">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83837614-selena-reiss?shelf=three-stars">three-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83837614-selena-reiss?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/83837614-selena-reiss?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3105348130" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer734312039715462894">TW: off-page suicide attempt referenced, homophobia, F-slur, blackmail<br/><br/>3 stars maybe?<br/><br/>Usually when I give three star ratings, it’s because I was disappointed or couldn’t connect fully to the book. This is not that kind of three star book. It was a surprise because I wasn’t expecting to get attached at all.<br/><br/>Let’s talk about what this book is. It is a deeply character-driven, older YA contemporary focused on living with the characters and getting very small details in their life. It reminded me of Th</span>
  <span id="freeText734312039715462894" style="display:none">TW: off-page suicide attempt referenced, homophobia, F-slur, blackmail<br /><br />3 stars maybe?<br /><br />Usually when I give three star ratings, it’s because I was disappointed or couldn’t connect fully to the book. This is not that kind of three star book. It was a surprise because I wasn’t expecting to get attached at all.<br /><br />Let’s talk about what this book is. It is a deeply character-driven, older YA contemporary focused on living with the characters and getting very small details in their life. It reminded me of The Miseducation if Cameron Post in that way. I don’t tend to love that combination all the time, but somehow in circa-2008 YA contemporary it surprises me with how much it works. This is a slow, lazy book that starts quite heavy and gets lighter, about internal journeys and character relationships, specifically the central one between two brothers who need to get to know each other again. This is a really hard story structure to pull of but I think this book did it.<br /><br />I wasn’t overly attached to any of the characters or their relationships, but I enjoyed reading about them. I do think the internal, emotional journey could’ve been clearer; new YA like this is often paired with the much closer first person, while older YA often used third person, which lended a bit of distance that didn’t aid in clarifying the characters’ feelings nor their reasoning behind pretty significant choices. <br /><br />However, I do have some serious flaws to mention, especially those interested because this is, in fact, LGBTQ+ fiction. Part of the reason why I knocked the rating down does have to do with some clunky sexism that I think was meant to make the teen boy protagonists (one in particular) seem like authentic teen boys. And I understand that authentic teen boys are sexist a good bit of the time, in exactly the casual ways this book shows. But it got to be a bit much and felt a bit clunky or forced, and it definitely took me out of the story.<br /><br />Then for the LGBTQ+ stuff. This takes place in a very conservative world in a less progressive time, and so pretty blatant homophobia is the norm. The F-slur is used several times, by both straight characters in a derogatory fashion and gay characters who just seem to see it as... a word. A descriptor. Not exactly reclaiming. If any of that will be triggering, I highly recommend you skip this, although I can say there is no assault due to homophobia. Furthermore, this is clearly old. There is no mention of the LGBTQ+ community; there is only being gay. The way things are discussed has aged. That’s not necessarily a bad thing, but know what you’re getting into. This book is 12 years old, and the community and its portrayal in media has changed. There’s very real issues other than just the aging though, which I’ll discuss below as they are spoilers.***<br /><br />Overall, I enjoyed this book. It definitely has its flaws— don’t get me wrong. But it was a nice, engrossing read.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />***SPOILERS PERTINENT TO THE LGBTQ+ REP:<br /><br /><br />Also, there’s a hint of the “bully-might-be-a-bully-because-he’s-secretly-gay” trope, which I hate, and we basically have a character solve a blackmail situation through another blackmail situation. This doesn’t combat negative stereotypes of gay people and it doesn’t combat the homophobia that a threat of outing entails.</span>
  <a data-text-id="734312039715462894" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


